name: Thomas Massie
content:
Tonight, I introduced legislation to prevent members of the Armed Forces from being forced to take the COVID-19 vaccine. My bill, HR 3860, prevents federal funds from being used to require a member of the Armed Forces to receive a vaccination against COVID-19. It also prevents adverse disciplinary action against military personnel who refuse the vaccine.

Members of the Armed Forces should not be forced to take this vaccine, and many federal policymakers continue to ignore science. For instance, many refuse to recognize the benefits of natural immunity gained from prior infection.

There is also evidence that young men may suffer increased rates of illnesses possibly linked to the COVID-19 vaccine. For example, according to the story linked below:

"Researchers in Israel say they've found a possible link between the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine and cases of heart inflammation in young men ages 16 to 30, according to a report submitted this week to the country's Ministry of Health. The report concluded that around 1 in 5,000 men who receive the vaccine may experience this side effect, known as myocarditis, which is higher than the rate seen for the whole vaccinated population during that time period, which was 1 in 50,000."

Current cosponsors of the legislation include Rep. Chip Roy, Rep. Lance Gooden, Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene, Rep. Lauren Boebert, Rep. Scott Perry, Rep. Greg Steube, Rep. Andy Biggs, Rep. Andrew Clyde, Rep. Tim Burchett, Rep. Jeff Duncan, Rep. Paul Gosar, and Rep. Alex Mooney. I am pleased to have their support to protect our troops.

https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/is-the-covid-19-vaccine-causing-rare-myocarditis-cases/ar-AAKJZSw

name: Thomas Massie
content:
During Thursday's oversight hearing for the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), I asked FBI Director Christopher Wray to commit to an expedited review of the agency's 9/11 files. The purpose of this review will be to determine whether the FBI can provide additional information to the families of 9/11 victims who are suing Saudi Arabia pursuant to congressional legislation.

Congress passed the Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act (JASTA) to ensure that the 9/11 families' case against Saudi Arabia could proceed. In 2018, the 9/11 families issued a subpoena for records that are critical to that lawsuit. According to lawyers for the victims' families, the FBI has refused to search its complete files for responsive documents, claiming that the process would be too burdensome. The lawyers also claim that the FBI has continued to withhold key documents and has significantly redacted others, even though the records concern events that occurred 20 years ago.

I asked Director Wray to commit to an expedited review of the FBI's documents to produce relevant information to the 9/11 families to the fullest extent possible. Furthermore, I asked the Director to request that the Director of National Intelligence review documents that have previously been withheld to reconsider whether they can be released to the families. I am pleased to report that Director Wray has promised to take action to further these goals.

The FBI must not sacrifice justice for the 9/11 families over concerns about diplomacy. On behalf of these families, I am pleased that Director Wray's public promise may lead to the release of additional evidence.

President Biden has presented a false choice between total withdrawal fromh Afghanistan and a forever war. But there‚Äôs a third option: Leave a small contingency of troops for a limited timeframe to accomplish critical security objectives.

As we saw after President Obama‚Äôs withdrawal from Iraq in 2011, terrorists will exploit a security vacuum. Two and a half years after U.S. troops left Iraq, ISIS captured Mosul. It took five years, tens of thousands of troops and more than 30,000 airstrikes to destroy the physical caliphate.

An expert report to the United Nations Security Council forecasts a similar outcome in Afghanistan now and observes that al Qaeda and other militants are celebrating President Biden‚Äôs decision as a ‚Äúvictory . . . for global radicalism.‚Äù

Reconsidering pivotal decisions is a sign of wisdom, not weakness, and I urge Mr. Biden to reconsider his choice on Afghanistan.

name: Ralph Norman
content:
Right now, my congressional office here in South Carolina is absolutely swamped with passport expedition requests. The numbers are through the roof.

Much of this is being driven by some really good vacation deals right now, particularly to touristy places in Mexico and the Caribbean. Many of these trips require folks to fly out relatively soon ‚Äì like within a week or two.

*** That‚Äôs a problem if you don‚Äôt already have a current passport!

Routine processing for both new passports and renewals can take up to 12 weeks, according to the State Department. Even paying extra to have your passport expedited can take 4-6 weeks. So you‚Äôll want to consider that before booking any travel requiring a passport.

If you find yourself in a pinch and need a passport on short notice, please pick up the phone and call my office at (803) 327-1114. There are absolutely no guarantees, and every situation is different. Depending on your circumstances, we may be able to help move things along at the State Department.

Additionally, if you‚Äôre considering international travel anytime in the foreseeable future, NOW is the time to make sure your passport is current and get the ball rolling if you need a renewal or a new passport. Don‚Äôt wait.

Thankfully we‚Äôre on the back side of COVID. The good news is that summer is here, and many people are in the mood to jet off somewhere. But please don‚Äôt forget about the status of your passport when making your travel plans!

name: Bob Gibbs
content:
This weekend, we marked 100 days since Republican Members on the House Oversight and Reform Committee first called on Chairwoman Maloney to hold a hearing on President Biden‚Äôs southern border crisis. Since then, we have called for a hearing two more times, all the while thousands of children and families were and still are being held at overcrowded facilities during a global pandemic.

President Biden has further fueled this humanitarian crisis with the cancellation of the Migrant Protection Protocols and returning to the failed ‚Äúcatch and release‚Äù method and continuing to push open border nonsense. Illegal border crossing levels are the highest they‚Äôve been in 21 years. Since President Biden took office, 61,000 illegal migrants have been released into the United States. Illegal crossings in January of 2021 were up 380% from January of 2020.

During her recent trip to Guatemala and Mexico, Vice President Harris (the Biden-appointed Border Czar) laughed on more than one occasion when asked about visiting the border, and even went as far as to attempt to lie about having already visited since taking office. Even Guatemalan President Alejandro Giammattei recently said the Biden administration‚Äôs relaxed message on immigration contributed to the surge in illegal border crossings that has put tens of thousands of people, especially children, in danger at the hands of coyotes and human traffickers.

The situation at our southern border is a serious national security, economic, health and environmental crisis. The Biden administration either refuses to or is incapable of tackling the very crisis they have created, and their inaction will only make it worse and put the most vulnerable in harm‚Äôs way.

name: Lisa Murkowski
content:
The United States Postal Service (USPS) posted in the Federal Register a notice their plan to change the delivery standards for First Class, package services (media mail, library mail, bound printed matter), marketing, and periodical mail. Essentially, this means Alaskans and Hawaiians will have to wait even longer than the Lower 48 to get their mail. The public comment period for this action ends on June 22. Comments may be e-mailed to PCFederalRegister@usps.gov, with the subject line of ‚ÄúService Standards for Market-Dominant Mail Products‚Äù or mailed to Manager, Product Classification, U.S. Postal Service, 475 L'Enfant Plaza SW, Room 4446, Washington, DC 20260-3436. The Postal Regulatory Commission is also taking comments until this Friday, June 18. Those who want to comment to the PRC must create a Temporary Account (link below). I strongly encourage Alaskans to make their voices heard.

PRC.GOV
Apply Online for a Temporary Account | Postal Regulatory Commission

name: Alan S. Lowenthal
content:
I'm proud that I was able to secure the inclusion of significant policy priorities I have championed in a major transportation legislative package currently moving through the House. These priorities included funding for regional transportation projects, major investments in freight goods movement, as well as initiatives to reduce carbon pollution and invest in electric vehicle infrastructure.

The $547 billion surface transportation reauthorization legislation, the INVEST in America Act, passed the House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee after a nearly 24-hour long markup on Wednesday. The bill is aimed at modernizing infrastructure nationwide and is built on the efforts of H.R. 2, the Moving Forward Act, which passed the House with my support last Congress. The INVEST in America Act is expected to be voted on by the full House later this month. The bill will provide a policy framework to support the American Jobs Plan, which will include critical, additional investments in our infrastructure.

name: Tom Cole
content:
On this day in 1777, the Continental Congress adopted a resolution formally recognizing the American flag:

"Resolved, That the flag of the United States shall be of thirteen stripes of alternate red and white: that the union be thirteen stars, white in a blue field, representing the new constellation."

After more than two centuries and several flag designs later, "Old Glory" remains a powerful symbol worldwide for liberty and freedom. Happy Flag Day!

name: Aumua Amata Coleman Radewagen
content: Today marks 244 years since the adoption of the U.S. flag. In American Samoa, earlier each year on April 17th, our own Flag Day is our most celebrated non-religious holiday, and we celebrate this same beautiful flag that dates back to June 14, 1777. On that day, the Continental Congress voted for it to become the permanent symbol of the new Republic for which they were risking their lives. Often called ‚ÄòOld Glory,‚Äô the United States flag has an illustrious history. The field of stars has been updated 15 times, most recently with our Pacific neighbors, Hawaii and Alaska. Just last week, the world remembered D-Day, the great effort to liberate a continent, with much valor and sacrifice, under the flags of the U.S. and close allies. We can feel healthy pride and patriotism to be a part of the United States. On this anniversary, we honor the U.S. flag and its ideals of freedom. The flag is prominent in this historic 1957 photo, showing Governor Uifa‚Äôatali Peter T. Coleman in Tutuila.

content:
Before I flew back to DC for this week‚Äôs votes, I stopped by small businesses in Juneau. These mom-and-pop stores were facing the loss of yet another summer cruise season until our Delegation was able to get the Alaska Tourism Restoration Act unanimously passed and signed into law. Soon, they‚Äôll be able to once again welcome visitors to Juneau and send them home with memories, food, and souvenirs.

I want to thank Deb Bergmann and her son Scott for hosting me at the Alaskan Fudge Company. This Alaskan-grown business has been producing delicious fudge in our state since 1980, and I am grateful for their contributions to our local economy. If you‚Äôre visiting Alaska this summer, I hope you‚Äôll patronize some of our many locally owned establishments.

We‚Äôll see you in Alaska very soon!

content:
This past weekend, I stopped by the Rocky Mountain Arsenal National Wildlife Refuge to help celebrate the announcement of additional funding to expand their Urban Wildlife Conservation Program. This additional support will help continue community partnerships and make important investments in maintenance and infrastructure to accommodate growing visitation and ensure new visitors are able to take full advantage of this local gem.

Our region is a large, urban hub but this place brings nature and species like bison, eagles, and black-footed ferrets to the doorstep of hundreds of thousands of Coloradans, enticing children and their families to get outside and experience nature at its best.

Early into my tenure as Chair of the Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness, I was approached by several military families about the abhorrent living conditions they were subjected to from privately constructed military housing units. I applaud the Department of Justice for pursuing justice for the military families who were harmed by these unsafe military housing units. As Readiness Chair, I will remain steadfast in my determination to right these wrongs and ensure no family is subjected to these unconscionable living conditions again

name: Steve Chabot
content: Happy Flag Day. Today marks the 244th birthday of the American Flag. On this date in 1777, the Second Continental Congress adopted our nation's first flag, which consisted of thirteen stars and thirteen stripes to represent the original thirteen colonies. While the flag has changed numerous times over the years, the fundamental truths brought forth by our Founding Fathers -- that "all men are created equal" and "are endowed by their Creator with certain unalienable rights" including "Life, Liberty and the pursuit of Happiness" -- are as important today as they were then. God bless you and your families, and God bless America!

name: Richard Hudson
content:
As we celebrate the 246th birthday of the U.S. Army today, I could think of no better news: Service members will soon have health care protections they deserve all thanks to the Rich Stayskal Act signed into law by President Trump in 2019.

I first met Sfc. Rich Stayskal, a Green Beret and Purple Heart recipient from Pinehurst, in 2018 after his stage 4 cancer had been misdiagnosed. Unfortunately, service members were not able to claim medical malpractice at the time.

But after 3 years of hard work, we changed the law and now starting soon, soldiers and service members like Rich will finally have equal access to health care protections.

The COVID-19 pandemic ravaged all aspects of the tourism and hospitality industry, a crucial sector that supports our economy and thousands of good-paying jobs in Alaska. Fortunately, against great odds, we were able to salvage a portion of Alaska‚Äôs crucial 2021 summer cruise ship season. name: Aumua Amata Coleman Radewagen
content: Happy birthday to the United States Army! Today, we honor the anniversary of the Army‚Äôs founding, which dates back to June 14, 1775, the year before the Declaration of Independence. Our men and women in our all-volunteer Army serve for many good reasons. As generations of soldiers before them have done, they serve the cause of freedom, and the security of the U.S. and our allies. It‚Äôs an important job, often a calling for many, and they do it well. name: John R. Curtis

Today I introduced the bipartisan Foreign Corruption Accountability Act with Congressman Tom Malinowski to authorize sanctions against people who engage in corruption against Americans abroad.

The Foreign Corruption Accountability Act is the second to be introduced in a series of bills as part of Counter-Kleptocracy Month #KleptoMonth, an initiative of the bipartisan Caucus against Foreign Corruption and Kleptocracy.

This bill closes a loophole in sanction authority which was discovered after a cobalt mine owner bribed the Congolese military to extort land from a U.S. business owner. As I mentioned in last week‚Äôs #CurtisClimateChat, cobalt production is predicted to grow rapidly and we must ensure clean energy supply chains are free from corruption and human rights abuses.

CURTIS.HOUSE.GOV

name: Dwight Evans
content:
Veterans and family members of veterans, claim YOUR vaccine dose this Saturday in Philly!

Philadelphia VA Medical Center
June 11 at 1:24 PM ¬∑

There are still Veterans, former US Military members, Veteran spouses and caregivers, Veteran children ages 18+ and CHAMPVA recipients who are not yet vaccinated against COVID-19. Please don't play Russian Roulette with your life! The Delta variant from India is on the rise here in the USA and it's more contagious and dangerous than the original SARS-CoV-2 coronavirus that hit the US shores in late 2019. We have partnered with the Laborers Local 57 Union to hold a FREE, one-shot COVID-19 vaccine clinic on Saturday, June 19, 2021 from 8am to 12pm at their Union offices at 500-506 North 6th Street (at the corner of 6th and Spring Garden Streets). Come out and protect your health, your loved ones and your community. GET VACCINATED! Veterans, former US Military members (regardless of discharge status), Veteran spouses/caregivers, Veteran children ages 18+ and CHAMPVA recipients ... ALL are welcome. See you then!

name: Tom Cole
content:
Did you know that every three seconds, someone is in need of a blood transfusion? Although life is beginning to return to a new normal amid the ongoing pandemic, the supply of blood nationwide remains critically low due to fewer donations. Donor blood is not just important during emergencies, but also for those undergoing major surgery, cancer treatments, hemorrhaging from childbirth or battling sickle cell disease.

On World Blood Donor Day, we recognize that donating blood saves lives. Find a local blood center at the link below.

AMERICASBLOOD.ORG
